<section xml:id="sec-transformations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Transformations of Functions</title>
  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>Use graphs of basic functions and the following operations to graph general functions.</p>
    </introduction>
    <ol>
      <li>
	Vertical Translation
      </li>
      <li>
	Horizontal Translation
      </li>
      <li>
	Vertical Scaling,
      </li>
      <li>
	Horizontal Scaling, and
      </li>
      <li>
	Reflection.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Graphing arbitrary functions can be a difficult task and the general methods are beyond the scope of basic algebra.
      However, if we know the graph of a function, <m>f</m>, and we can write another function, <m>g</m>, in terms of <m>f</m> in a specific way, then we can use the graph of <m>f(x)</m> to graph <m>g(x)</m> using <em>transformations</em>.
      In this seciton, we discuss three types of transformations: translation, scaling, and reflection.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Translation</title>
    <p>
      Throughout this section, assume that the graph of the function <m>y = f(x)</m> is known.
    </p>
    
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Vertical Translation</title>
      
      <definition>
	<title>Vertical Translation</title>
	<p>
	  Let <m>c</m> be a positive number.
	  We say the function <m>g(x)</m> is a <term>vertical translation</term>
	  <idx>
	    <h>Graph</h>
	    <h>Tranformation</h>
	    <h>Translation</h>
	    <h>Vertical</h>
	  </idx>
	  of the function <m>f(x)</m> if <m>g(x) = f(x) \pm c</m>.
	</p>
	<ul>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The graph of <m>g(x) = f(x) + c</m> is obtained by shifting the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> up the <m>y</m>-axis by <m>c</m> units.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The graph of <m>g(x) = f(x) - c</m> is obtained by shifting the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> down the <m>y</m>-axis by <m>c</m>-units.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ul>
      </definition>
      
      <example>
	<statement>
	  <p>
	    Use <xref ref="fig-parabola" text="title"/> to graph the functions <m>g(x) = x^2 + 2</m> and <m>h(x) = x^2 - 3</m>.
	  </p>
	</statement>
	<solution>
	  <p>
	    The graph of <m>g(x)</m> is obtained by shifting the graph of <m>f(x)</m> up the <m>y</m>-axis by <m>2</m> units, and the graph of <m>h(x)</m> is obtained by shifting the graph of <m>f(x)</m> down the <m>y</m>-axis by 3 units.
	  </p>
	  <figure>
	    <image>
	      <latex-image>
		<xi:include parse="text" href="tex/vertical_translation.tex"/>
	      </latex-image>
	    </image>
	  </figure>
	</solution>
      </example>
    </subsubsection>
    
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Horizontal Translation</title>

      <definition>
	<title>Horizontal Translation</title>
	<p>
	  Let <m>c</m> be a positive number.
	  We say the function <m>g(x)</m> is a <term>horizontal translation</term>
	  <idx>
	    <h>Graph</h>
	    <h>Tranformation</h>
	    <h>Translation</h>
	    <h>Horizontal</h>
	  </idx>
	  of the function <m>f(x)</m> if <m>g(x) = f(x \pm c)</m>.
	</p>
	<ul>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The graph of <m>g(x) = f(x - c)</m> is obtained by shifting the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> to the right along the <m>x</m>-axis by <m>c</m> units.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      The graph of <m>g(x) = f(x + c)</m> is obtained by shifting the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> to the left along the <m>x</m>-axis by <m>c</m>-units.
	    </p>
	  </li>
	</ul>
      </definition>

      <example>
	<statement>
	  <p>
	    Use <xref ref="fig-parabola" text="title"/> to graph the functions <m>g(x) = (x+2)^2</m> and <m>h(x) = (x-3)^2</m>.
	  </p>
	  <figure>
	    <image>
	      <latex-image>
		<xi:include parse="text" href="tex/parabola.tex"/>
	      </latex-image>
	    </image>
	    <caption>The graph of <m>y = x^2</m>.</caption>
	  </figure>
	</statement>
	<solution>
	  <p>
	    The graph of <m>g(x)</m> is obtained by shifting the graph of <m>f(x)</m> to the left along the <m>x</m>-axis by <m>2</m> units, and the graph of <m>h(x)</m> is obtained by shifting the graph of <m>f(x)</m> to the right along the <m>x</m>-axis by 3 units.
	  </p>
	  <figure>
	    <image>
	      <latex-image>
		<xi:include parse="text" href="tex/horizontal_translation.tex"/>
	      </latex-image>
	    </image>
	  </figure>
	</solution>
      </example>
    </subsubsection>

  </subsection>

  

